The inaccuracies as to matters of fact, which are commented on in the notes, do not detract from the merit of the speech: as instances of oratorical intensification (δείνωσις, Quintil v 2 ξ 24) we may refer to the pic- tures of Mithridates (ἕξ 32—34) and of the dangers to be dreaded from the‘accomplices of Catiline (§§ 78-8 5).

It is always to be remembered that we have the speech not as it was delivered (see on ξ 57), but as it was prepared for publica- tion ; and it is not unlikely that some of the more finished passages (such as ἐξ 62-65) received their last touch after the trial.
